  "tables": [
    {
      "block_id": "23c4750c-f3ba-8071-bb74-f0874bf2afe4",
      "heading": "Summary Table REC",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Recommender System Type",
          "Target of Recommendation",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Initialization Method",
          "Updates to Recommendations",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Recommendation types",
          "Evaluation",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Higher Education",
          "Blended Learning",
          "Collaborative Filtering",
          "Optimal Learning Policy",
          "198 undergraduate students",
          "Multiple Courses in a Software Engineering Program",
          "Course Learning Outcomes, CLO marks, PLO Description, Course Information",
          "The start state is based on Cosine similarity → which measures the degree of similarity between the learner’s CLOs and each Bi-Cluster.",
          "Recommendations are designed in a way that maximizes what the author’s call return.\n",
          "Dataset preparation involves the mapping of courses to CLOs (which are themselves mapped to PLOs and OBEs)- Students are assigned a score on CLO based on their marks - leading to the creation of a student CLO matrix.\n\nStudents are bi-clustered (in a way that a student can be assigned to different CLO sets - using Bibit - which requires converting CLO scores to 1/0 form. \n\nAfter forming the bi-clustersm the authors attempted to merge them absed on Jaccard similarity.\n\n",
          "Recommendation for current defficient CLO",
          "{Precision: 0.4241 - 500 episodes, Recall: 0.5389 - 500 episodes. F1-Score: 0.47420 - 500 episodes, CLO Coverage: 0.8045 - 450 episodes, Student Coverage: 0.9827 - 350 episodes onward}",
          "Authors use Reinforcement Learning to create “optimal learning paths”. \n\nAuthors start with the creation of bi-clusters, and  these bi-clusters will be used as reference for trainining along a Square Grid. \n\nFrom here, Q-Learning is used to learn the optimal policy for the student in question. \n\nAuthors do a set of tests comparing the optimal policy against other randomly generated policies. Evaluation is done via comparison of prediction of a deficient CLO for a student vs actual deficient CLOs. Performance is tested on multiple episodes and the model is shown to be better at later iterations.\n\nAuthros also perform different optimizations of parameters.",
          "- Training requires labels for deficient CLOs. \n\n- Only uses Q-Learn to solve the Reinforcement Learning problem. \n\n- Only Bibit is explored as a clustering approach.\n\n- Does not use student information beyibd the CLO scores for each student. \n\nCan only use used retrospectively: can only identify CLOs and make suggestions for CLOs taken in previous semesters.\n\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 10
    }
  ],
